<!-- Use the Introduction section to give a brief overview of what
     the application is and what it does. -->
  <sect1 id="synaptic-introduction"> 
    <title>Introduction</title> 
    <para>The &app; enables you to manage your software.
    The software is organizied in so called packages and 
    &app; features upgrading, installing, removing or even
    downgrading of such software packages.</para>
    
    <para>Modifcations on the status of packages are not immediatly 
    executed. &app; collects the planned modifications in a queue 
    and commits them to apt. Apt is an unified package manager backend 
    for RPM and DEB systems.
    </para>
    <para>You can start <application>&app;</application> in the following ways:
    </para> 
    <variablelist>
    	<varlistentry>
    		<term><guimenu>Applications</guimenu> menu</term>
    		<listitem>
    		<para>Choose 
    		<menuchoice>
    		<guisubmenu>Preferences</guisubmenu>
		<guisubmenu>System Tools</guisubmenu>
    		<guimenuitem>Software</guimenuitem>
    		</menuchoice>. </para>
    		</listitem>
    	</varlistentry>
    	<varlistentry>
    		<term>Command line</term>
    		<listitem>
    		<para>To start <application>&app;</application> from a command line, type the following command, 
    		then press <keycap>Return</keycap>:</para>
    		<para> 
			<command>synaptic</command> 
    		</para> 
    		</listitem>
    	</varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect1>

